    {
      "question": "The graph of a polynomial $p(x)$ is given. It is observed that the graph intersects the $x$-axis at exactly two distinct points $A(-3, 0)$ and $B(2, 0)$ and intersects the $y$-axis at the point $C(0, -6)$. (i) Based on the geometrical meaning of zeros, state the number of zeros of $p(x)$ and list them. (ii) If the polynomial is of the form $p(x) = ax^2 + bx + c$, find the values of $a$, $b$, and $c$.",
      "answer": "(i) The number of zeros is $2$; the zeros are $x = -3$ and $x = 2$. (ii) $a = 1$, $b = 1$, $c = -6$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the zeros from the x-coordinates of the points where the graph intersects the x-axis.",
          "Use the factored form of the quadratic polynomial $p(x) = k(x - \\alpha)(x - \\beta)$, where $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ are the zeros.",
          "Substitute the given zeros into the factored form to get $p(x) = k(x + 3)(x - 2)$.",
          "Use the y-intercept point $(0, -6)$ to solve for the constant $k$ by setting $p(0) = -6$.",
          "Expand the expression to find the coefficients $a$, $b$, and $c$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = k(x - (-3))(x - 2) = k(x + 3)(x - 2) \\\\ p(0) = k(0 + 3)(0 - 2) = -6 \\\\ k(3)(-2) = -6 \\\\ -6k = -6 \\Rightarrow k = 1 \\\\ p(x) = 1(x^2 - 2x + 3x - 6) = x^2 + x - 6 \\\\ a = 1, b = 1, c = -6$"
      },
